udy of astrology challenges ready-made assumptions about the boundaries between "science" and "superstition," "rationality" and "magic." Rather than judging the validity of astrology as a knowledge system, Caterina Guenzi explores astrological counseling as a social practice and how it "works from within" for both astrologers and their clients. She examines the points of view of those who use astrology either as a way of earning their living or as a means through which to solve problems and make decisions, concluding that, because astrology combines mathematical calculations and astronomical observations with ritual practices, it provides educated urban families with an idiom through which modern science and devotional Hinduism can be subsumed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAstrologerszIndiazVārānasi (Uttar Pradesh). 0aAstrologerszIndiazVārānasi (Uttar Pradesh). 0aHindu astrologyxSocial aspectszIndiazVārānasi (Uttar Pradesh). 0aHindu astrologyxSocial aspectszIndiazVārānasi (Uttar Pradesh). 0aPredictive astrology. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Anthropology of Religion. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Cultural Anthropology. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Hindu Studies. 4aSociology : Sociology of Religion. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2021z978311149169140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848203340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438482033423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438482033/original  a978-3-11-149169-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles